<% help_title "Help on #{ TiaItem.model_name.human }" %>
  <div class="container">
    <%= helpcrumbs %>
    <%= help_header %>
    <p class="lead">Manage those in all <%= TiaList.model_name.human.pluralize -%>
      where you are assigned as owner of the item.</p>
    <h3>How to use</h3>
    <p>Use this feature to keep track of all
       <%= TiaList.model_name.human.pluralize -%> where the owner of the
       list (or his deputy) has assigned you as owner of this item. In order
       to view your items, you need also the permission to access this
       item. You may also have permission to update your items by
       adding a comment to the comment field.</p>
    <h3>Attributes of Items</h3>
    <p>Each Task, Issue, Action Item has the following attributes:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><%= help_param TiaItem.human_attribute_name( :code ) -%> is a unique
        identifier for each an every item in a specific list. Always use this code when
        referencing to specific item in the list.</li>
      <li>The <%= help_param TiaItem.human_attribute_name( :description ) %>
        explains the objective of this item.</li>
      <li><%= help_param TiaItem.human_attribute_name( :comment ) %> is a
        field available to hold any status information, or a summary of the
        solution of the problem. On the index page, this field is shown below the 
        <%= help_term TiaItem.human_attribute_name( :description ) %> field
        unless it is empty.
        If permitted, you can update this field to enter any new or additional
        information on this item, or the resolution of the issue.</li>
      <li><%= help_param TiaItem.human_attribute_name( :prio ) %> tells you 
        about the priority assigned to that item:
        <ol>
          <li>high</li>
          <li>medium</li>
          <li>low</li>
        </ol>
        Using the ABC analysis, this would map to 
        <ol class='upper-alpha'>
          <li>items that are perceived as being urgent and important,</li>
          <li>items that are important but not urgent, and</li>
          <li>all others, i.e. items that are not important (urgent or not).</li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li>The <%= help_param TiaItem.human_attribute_name( :owner ) %> is 
        always you.</li>
      <li>The <%= help_param TiaItem.human_attribute_name( :due_date ) %>
        gives the date when this task/issue/action item should be resolved.</li>
      <li>The <%= help_param TiaItem.human_attribute_name( :status ) %> of the
        item can be:
        <ul>
          <li><%= TiaItem::TIA_ITEM_STATUS_LABELS[ 0 ] -%> - just created or
            not yet resolved</li>
          <li><%= TiaItem::TIA_ITEM_STATUS_LABELS[ 1 ] -%> - waiting for other
            partiesâ€™ input or reaction</li>
          <li><%= TiaItem::TIA_ITEM_STATUS_LABELS[ 2 ] -%> - when this task,
            issue, or action item does not need to be traced anymore</li>
          <li><%= TiaItem::TIA_ITEM_STATUS_LABELS[ 3 ] -%> - when this task,
            issue, or action item is completed, resolved, or otherwise 
            finished</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>If an item is marked <%= help_param TiaItem.human_attribute_name( :archived )%>,
        it will not show up on any listings anymore.</li>
      <li>When viewing a specific item, the button labelled 
        <%= help_term I18n.t('button_label.history')-%>
        shows a table in reverse chronological order of all the changes done to this
        item: The top table shows the current status, the entries below the previous
        status at the given time.</li>
    </ul>
    <%= help_footer FEATURE_ID_OUR_TIA_ITEMS %> 
